<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-102-032  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 102 032.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Jan 29 1990 v24 n5 p86(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Selecting expert systems tools.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Keyes, Jessica.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Selecting expert systems is based on three criteria: the expertsystems features the application requires, the database or fileaccess required and the need to network the application.andP;  Thedifficulty of operation increases with the size of the equipment,so select a platform you can handle then choose the tool that bestfits your application.andP;  The more complex tools require largeplatforms.andP;  If a system requires immediate access to a mainframe,the more likely it will need to run on that platform.andP;  The betterthe network, the more likely you will be able to cut costs byrunning it on a microcomputer.andP;  Software selection is easy oncethe platform is chosen.andP;  There are a limited number of programsavailable for each platform and they exhibit many of the samecharacteristics.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Software SelectionExpert Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Decision support. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>